        <h2>Results</h2>

        <h3>Pharmacology of Drugs</h3>
        <h5>Mechanisms of Drug Action in the Brain</h5>
        <p>
          Drugs affect neurotransmitters in the brain. Some increase their
          release, others block their reuptake, or mimic their effect. For
          example, cocaine increases dopamine, causing euphoria; opioids relieve
          pain by binding to specific receptors; LSD affects serotonin, altering
          perception.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, cocaine blocks the reuptake of dopamine, leading to an
          increase in this substance in the brain and generating feelings of
          pleasure and euphoria. Opioids, such as morphine and heroin, bind to
          endorphin receptors and reduce the perception of pain. LSD affects
          serotonin, altering sensory perception and cognition.
        </p>

        <div class="section-image">
