        <h5>Types of Drugs and Their Effects</h5>
        <p>
          <strong>Stimulants</strong>: Increase the activity of the central
          nervous system. Examples include cocaine, amphetamines, and nicotine.
          Their effects include euphoria, increased heart rate, and temporary
          improvement in alertness.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Depressants</strong>: Decrease brain activity and can induce
          relaxation or sedation. Alcohol, barbiturates, and benzodiazepines
          belong to this category. Their abuse can lead to physical and
          psychological dependence.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Hallucinogens</strong>: Alter the perception of reality.
          Examples include LSD, psilocybin, and DMT. These drugs can induce
          psychedelic experiences, changes in consciousness, and sensory
          distortions.
        </p>

        <h5>Short-Term and Long-Term Effects</h5>
        <p>
          In the short term, effects depend on the substance and its use,
          ranging from pleasure to paranoia. In the long term, drugs can cause
          dependence, organ damage, and mental disorders. For instance,
          stimulants may cause psychosis; depressants, liver damage; and
          hallucinogens, lasting perceptual disturbances.
        </p>

