        <h3>Social Impact</h3>
        <p>
          Drug use has a profound impact on society, affecting not only users
          but also their families and communities. One of the most significant
          effects is the stigma and discrimination faced by users, which limits
          their access to healthcare, employment, and social support. This
          marginalization reinforces the cycle of drug use and reduces the
          chances of reintegration into society. The stigma also affects their
          families, who often experience social rejection and financial
          hardship.
        </p>

        <p>
          Drug use and trafficking are linked to various forms of violence, from
          conflicts between cartels and gangs to domestic and interpersonal
          violence. Certain substances can alter behavior and increase the risk
          of aggression. Moreover, the criminalization of drug use often leads
          to abuse of authority and institutional violence, shifting the
          response away from a public health approach.
        </p>

        <p>
          At the family level, problematic drug use causes strained
          relationships, abandonment, abuse, and financial instability. At the
          community level, it contributes to social breakdown, increased crime,
          loss of cohesion, and limited job opportunities. The lack of resources
          for support and rehabilitation only worsens the situation,
          perpetuating cycles of poverty and social exclusion.
        </p>

