        <h3>Prevention and Education</h3>

        <h5>Prevention Strategies</h5>
        <p>
          Drug prevention strategies include initiatives in various areas such
          as schools, communities, and government. In schools, prevention
          programs focus on early education about the risks of drug use,
          promoting decision-making skills and resistance to social pressure.
          Public awareness campaigns use media and social networks to
          disseminate information about the dangers of drug use and promote
          healthy lifestyles. Community initiatives aim to create safe and
          supportive environments, offering recreational and educational
          activities for young people.
        </p>

        <h5>Educational Programs</h5>
        <p>
          Drug education not only focuses on information about substances but
          also on strategies to strengthen youth resilience. Programs such as
          “D.A.R.E.” (Drug Abuse Resistance Education) in the United States and
          other international initiatives have been designed to equip students
          with tools to resist social pressure and make healthy decisions.
          Additionally, the role of the family is crucial in preventive
          education, as open communication and the establishment of clear rules
          can reduce the risk of drug use.
        </p>

