        <h3>Treatment and Recovery</h3>

        <h5>Treatment Methods</h5>
        <p>
          The treatment of drug addiction includes a combination of
          pharmacological and psychological approaches. Among pharmacological
          treatments are the use of methadone and buprenorphine for opioid
          addiction, as well as medications such as naltrexone and disulfiram
          for the treatment of alcoholism. In the psychological realm,
          cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) has proven effective in modifying
          thought and behavior patterns associated with drug use. Additionally,
          motivational and community reinforcement therapies have shown positive
          results in long-term recovery.
        </p>

        <h5>Relapse Management and Abstinence</h5>
        <p>
          Relapse is a common challenge in addiction recovery. Strategies such
          as individual counseling, group therapy, and the use of medications
          can help prevent relapse. The establishment of social support networks
          and participation in structured activities are also key factors in
          maintaining abstinence. Additionally, access to ongoing care programs
          and professional follow-up increase the chances of successful
          recovery.
        </p>

