        <h3>Research and Statistics</h3>

        <h5>Recent Studies</h5>
        <p>
          Research in the field of addiction has advanced significantly in
          recent decades. Recent studies explore new treatments, such as
          psychedelic-assisted therapy, which has shown promising results in
          addiction to substances like alcohol and nicotine. Research also
          examines the impact of social determinants, such as unemployment,
          poverty, and lack of access to education, on drug use. Additionally,
          personalized medicine approaches, based on genetics and neuroscience,
          are being developed to improve the effectiveness of treatments.
        </p>

        <h5>Consumption Statistics</h5>
        <p>
          Monitoring drug use trends is essential for designing public policies.
          Global reports, such as those published by the United Nations Office
          on Drugs and Crime (UNODC), show consumption patterns, regional
          differences, and changes in the most commonly used substances. For
          example, in recent years, there has been an increase in the use of
          synthetic opioids, such as fentanyl, in various parts of the world,
          leading to a public health crisis in countries like the United States
          and Canada.
        </p>

