        <h3>Drugs and Art/Culture</h3>
        <p>
          Many artists and writers have used drugs to get ideas for their work.
          For example, Aldous Huxley wrote about his experience with mescaline,
          and this helped start the psychedelic movement. Writers like William
          S. Burroughs also wrote about drugs to explore new ideas and criticize
          society.
        </p>
        <p>
          In visual art, we can see how drugs have influenced styles, especially
          in the 1960s. Some artists used bright colors and strange shapes to
          show the effects of drugs like LSD. People still study how drugs
          affect creativity.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the 1960s and 1970s, the hippie movement used drugs to try to
          understand life in a deeper way. This changed music, clothes, and art
          at that time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Drugs have also been important in popular culture. Many songs talk
          about drug use, sometimes in a negative way, and sometimes in a
          positive way. Movies like Trainspotting and Requiem for a Dream show
          how drugs can hurt people. Other films, like Fear and Loathing in Las
          Vegas, show drugs in a wild and strange way.
        </p>
        <p>
          Fashion has also taken ideas from drugs, with styles that use bright
          colors and patterns. Today, TV shows and documentaries on streaming
          platforms help people learn more about drugs, their dangers, and drug
          laws. For example, the show Narcos talks about cocaine, and some
          documentaries show the problem of opioids in the U.S.
        </p>

