        <h3>International Perspectives</h3>
        <p>
          Different countries have different drug laws. Some, like Portugal, do
          not send people to jail for using drugs. Instead, they help them with
          health care and treatment. This has reduced the number of deaths from
          overdoses.
        </p>
        <p>
          Other countries, like the Philippines, have very strict laws. These
          laws have caused more violence and problems with human rights. In the
          United States, some states have made cannabis legal. This has started
          new conversations about legalizing other drugs. In Latin America, some
          countries have changed their drug laws to protect poor communities.
        </p>
        <p>
          To stop drug trafficking, countries need to work together.
          Organizations like the UN, OAS, and Interpol share information, arrest
          drug traffickers, and take away their money and goods.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some programs help farmers grow legal crops instead of drugs. These
          programs work better when governments support them and have enough
          money.
        </p>
        <p>
          Today, there are new synthetic drugs that are hard to control.
          Countries must cooperate to make better laws and stop these new drugs
          from spreading.
        </p>

