        <h2>Conclusions</h2>

        <h3>Legislation and Drug Policies</h3>
        <p>
          Drug policies vary significantly across countries and have evolved
          over time to strike a balance between public safety and individual
          rights. International agreements, like the 1961 Single Convention on
          Narcotic Drugs, have established frameworks for regulating substances.
          However, national strategies differ: some countries enforce strict
          prohibition, while others, like Portugal, treat drug use as a public
          health issue, and countries like Uruguay and Canada have legalized
          cannabis under state- regulated systems.
        </p>
        <p>
          In contrast, punitive models like the U.S. “War on Drugs” have led to
          high incarceration rates, especially among users and small-scale
          dealers, raising questions about the effectiveness of criminalization.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some nations have adopted harm reduction policies that aim to minimize
          the negative consequences of drug use without criminalizing users.
          These include needle exchange programs, supervised consumption sites,
          substitution therapies like methadone, and public education campaigns.
          Countries such as Switzerland and Canada have seen positive results,
          including fewer overdose deaths and a drop in infectious diseases.
        </p>
        <p>
          The legalization of cannabis in several countries has fueled debates
          over whether to regulate other substances. Supporters highlight
          benefits like quality control, crime reduction, and increased tax
          revenue, while critics warn about the potential rise in use and the
          challenges of implementing proper regulations.
        </p>

